06875nam a22008055i 9780226012858DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20102010ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226012858  a(DE-B1597)524184  a(OCoLC)1135613975  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a332.49422200aEurope and the Euro /ced. by Francesco Giavazzi, Alberto Alesina. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (624 p.) :b81 line drawings, 71 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNational Bureau of Economic Research Conference Report00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Breakup of the Euro Area -- t2. The Euro and Structural Reforms -- t3. The Euro and Firm Restructuring -- t4. Business Cycles in the Euro Area -- t5. The Estimated Trade Effects of the Euro: Why Are They Below Those from Historical Monetary Unions among Smaller Countries? -- t6. A New Metric for Banking Integration in Europe -- t7. Why the European Securities Market Is Not Fully Integrated -- t8. The Euro and Fiscal Policy -- t9. How Central Bankers See It: The First Decade of European Central Bank Policy and Beyond -- t10. Reevaluating Swedish Membership in the European Monetary Union: Evidence from an Estimated Model -- t11. Euro Membership as a U.K. Monetary Policy Option: Results from a Structural Model -- tContributors -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is rare for countries to give up their currencies and thus their ability to influence such critical aspects of their economies as interest and exchange rates. Yet ten years ago a number of European countries did exactly that when they adopted the euro. Despite some dissent, there were a number of arguments in favor of this policy change: it would facilitate exchange of goods, money, and people by decreasing costs; it would increase trade; and it would enhance efficiency and competitiveness at the international level. A decade is an ideal time frame over which to evaluate the success of the euro and whether it has lived up to expectations. To that aim, Europe and the Euro looks at a number of important issues, including the effects of the euro on reform of goods and labor markets; its influence on business cycles and trade among members; and whether the single currency has induced convergence or divergence in the economic performance of member countries. While adoption of the euro may not have met the expectations of its most optimistic proponents, the benefits have been many, and there is reason to believe that the euro is robust enough to survive recent economic shocks. This volume is an essential reference on the first ten years of the euro and the workings of a monetary union.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEurovCongresses. 0aEurozonevCongresses. 0aMonetary policyzEuropean Union countriesvCongresses. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  amoney, finance, financial, economy, economics, wealth, coins, currencies, currency, critical, european, western, change, progress, cost, trade, international, reform, goods, labor, markets, benefits, monetary, congress, policy, eu, union, eurozone, structural, institutional, securities, model, institutions, controversial, business, fiscal.1 aAlesina, Alberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlesina, Alberto, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aArdagna, Silvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBugamelli, Matteo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCecchetti, Stephen G., econtributor.4ctb4http